<font color="#FF0000">A BRIEF REMEMBERANCE</font><br>
<tt>Sun May 18 13:58:26 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Some years ago my toddler daughter and I stepped into a resturant for lunch.  I was wearing a jeans jacket profusely adorned with patches denoting Vietnam and Marine Corp service.  When it came time to pay the bill, I was informed that it had already been paid by the gentleman sitting a few booths away.  Glancing over, was a WWII era man sitting with his wife.  When I stopped to thank him, glancing at the, 'Vietnam Vet and Damn Proud of it' patch on my sleeve, he replied, &quot;No Son, we thank you.&quot;  At the time America had recently welcomed home the hostages with parades and yellow ribbons.  I had been back in 'the World' perhaps 15 years, and it was the first time I had been thanked.  Did I need it?  Not really.  I came home and knew that somehow, the pieces had to be picked up and it would be up to me.  Those pieces I would learn, were pretty scattered, with some broken beyond repair.  That simple thank you is treasured in my memory.  Not only was it the first, it was the last...<br>
I'm still proud, they'll never be able to take that from me. From reading through these prior messages, find that we all, (for the most part), have the same feelings.
<p><code>--   (Zingara) </code><p>


